- select and apply appropriate discrete structures to describe and reason about ordinary computer science situations;
- bring and present your own mathematical reasoning and evidence;

Valuation and attitude

- Identify and use suitable mathematical tools in common situations that arise in computer science;
- Assess and criticize mathematical reasoning and evidence performed by a third party.

- account for the concepts and constructions used in imperative programming;
- Describe and apply some standard algorithms, for example sorting and searching, as well as knowing where these are found in the language's standard library;
- Provide a basic account of objects and classes.

- use basic software development tools;
- Implementing simple and well -structured imperative programs according to informal specification;
- carry out an effective testing of these using appropriate tools;
- Use predefined data structures, such aslists and fields (arrays);
- Construct simple programs using classes and objects.

The course deals with imperative programming and algorithms in an object -oriented programming language.

The first part of the course presents imperative techniques and concepts:

- Programming with permission;
- Basic about types, primitive types and reference types;
- Literals, variables, initiation and allocation;
- Value and reference semes and alias problems;
- Declarations, operators, expressions, sentences and governing sentences (selection, iteration);
- Use of ready -made standard classes for I/O Handling and data structures for collections (eg lists);
- fields (arrays);
- Algorithms for e.g.search, sorting;
- Methods and parameter transfer;
- Error management.

The second part of the course gives a minimal introduction to the object -oriented environment:

- Basic concept in writing your own class, ie constructors, instance/class variables, instance/class methods and institution;
- Introduction to implementation heritage;
- Use of standard features to draw graphics.

The course also addresses working methods, idioms, basic quality aspects and testing and troubleshooting.

- effectively read scientific texts in computer science;
- Write clear, concise and ethical scientific texts in computer science;
- Communicate scientific results in computer science clearly to an audience with varying knowledge background;
- use correct English, orally and in writing.

- Critically review one's own scientific texts and texts written by others;
- compare and analyze scientific texts in computer science;
- Reflect on ethical aspects of scientific writing.

- Explain terminology, concept and theory linked to the chosen subject area;
- account for current methods and technologies in the chosen subject area;
- Analyze and carry out a development project that has a clear goal and a predefined result;

- Plan work, set interim goals, keep the project going, make realistic assessments of resource requirements and possible results;
- seek relevant literature and related results;
- present results clearly in oral and written form;
- Document the project so that others can build on it;

Valuation and attitude

- Evaluate and compare different solutions to the current problem;
- Draw conclusions from the results of the work.

- Describe algorithms and their characteristics: explain algorithms in writing, so that others can understand how they work, why they are correct and fast, and where they are useful;
- Realize that non-trivial calculation problems, which must be solved with the help of algorithms, appear in various real computer applications and formalize them;
- Intractability: recognize "intractable problems" and other classes of problems such as P, NP, NPC;
- Prove the correctness of algorithms.

-Design: Apply the most important design techniques for effective algorithms (eg greedy, dynamic programming, Divide-and-Conquer) to problems similar to the textbook examples but are new;
- Performing the entire development cycle of algorithms: problem analysis, choosing, modifying and combining appropriate techniques and data structures, analysis of correctness and complexity, finding possible improvements, etc.;
- Perform simple reductions between problems, explain NP completeness and recognize different calculation difficult problems that tend to emerge over and over in different applications.
